<h2 id="toc3"><span>SCP Authors</span></h2>
<p><span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/maliceaforethought" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2902864); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2902864&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1609721470" alt="MaliceAforethought" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2902864)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/maliceaforethought" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2902864); return false;">MaliceAforethought</a></span>: If I had to say, probably my biggest inspiration as an author and one of my favorites. There's a certain kind of&#8230; logistical amusement I get from their work that you might get from an MC Escher print, tossing and turning around the ideas in my head. Most of this shines through in the excellent <a href="http://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/domc-hub">Department of Miscommunications</a> series, and works such as <a href="/scp-4517">SCP-4517</a> and <a href="/scp-4773">SCP-4773</a> really demonstrate what I find so intriguing about their articles.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended Articles:</strong> <a href="/scp-5790">SCP-5790</a>, <a href="/scp-5856">SCP-5856</a></p>
<hr />
<p><span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2156983&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1609721470" alt="psul" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2156983)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;">psul</a></span>: The author of arguably some of the best uses of horror on the site. Something about their work just manages to get under my skin like nothing else, making you relate and sympathize with a certain character and pulling the rug out from under you. No better is this illustrated than in the wonderful tale <a href="/until-death">Until Death</a>, one of my favorites in how it transforms the original <a href="/scp-106">SCP-106</a> and mashes it with <a href="/scp-3001">SCP-3001</a> to make it delightfully terrifying. It's cool, check it out!</p>
<p><strong>Recommended Articles:</strong> <a href="/scp-2136">SCP-2136</a>, <a href="/scp-3515">SCP-3515</a></p>
<hr />
<p><span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3938622&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1609721470" alt="The Great Hippo" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3938622)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;">The Great Hippo</a></span>: Another great horror author. It feels like every one of their horror articles is a different flavor of scary &#8212; be it monstery (<a href="/scp-3035">SCP-3035</a>), minimalist (<a href="/scp-3561">SCP-3561</a>, <a href="/scp-4087">SCP-4087</a>), or just plain creepy (<a href="/scp-2571">SCP-2571</a>, <a href="/scp-2679">SCP-2679</a>), Hippo's got you covered.</p>
